text: Introduction
label: H4

text: BLISS, for Bi-Level Integrated System Synthesis, is an
label: BODY

text: optimization method for engineering a modular system,
label: BODY

text: e.g., an aerospace vehicle, in which it is beneficial to
label: BODY

text: separate the design variables and constraints local to a
label: BODY

text: module from those that govern the entire system.  Such
label: BODY

text: separation fosters development of a broad workfront of
label: BODY

text: people and computers, hence it fits well the current
label: BODY

text: trends for massively parallel processing in computer
label: BODY

text: technology and the concurrent engineering style of the
label: BODY

text: workforce organization.
label: BODY

text: The focus on dividing the optimization into the
label: BODY

text: suboptimizations within each module (subsystem, also
label: BODY

text: called the black box) and a coordinating optimization at
label: BODY

text: the system level places BLISS in the Multidisciplinary
label: BODY

text: Design Optimization (MDO) toolbox, in the company
label: BODY

text: of a few other methods that have the same focus as
label: BODY

text: BLISS but differ in approach.  Representative examples
label: BODY

text: of these methods are the Collaborative Optimization
label: BODY

text: American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics
label: BODY

text: (CO) (Braun et al, 1965), the Concurrent SubSpace
label: BODY

text: Optimization (CSSO) (Sobieszczanski-Sobieski, 1988,
label: BODY

text: Bloebaum et al, 1992), and the Concurrent Design
label: BODY

text: Optimization (Wujek et al, 1995).
label: BODY

text: The distinguishing features of BLISS are the use of the
label: BODY

text: system objective (e.g., the aircraft range) as the
label: BODY

text: optimization objective in each of the subsystems and at
label: BODY

text: the
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: level,

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: the
label: BODY

text: optimizations at the system and subsystem levels by
label: BODY

text: the optimum sensitivity derivatives with respect to
label: BODY

text: parameters.
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: Satisfactory results from the initial trials of BLISS on a
label: BODY

text: test case of a business jet encouraged next step in the
label: BODY

text: BLISS development - upgrading its structural analysis
label: BODY

text: and aerodynamic drag analysis modules - and validating
label: BODY

text: on the same test case.
label: BODY

text: This paper reports on the above BLISS upgrade and
label: BODY

text: results of the testing that advance the methods toward
label: BODY

text: becoming a tool suitable for practical applications.  The
label: BODY

text: report provides a synopsis of the BLISS method,
label: BODY

text: describes the salient features of the two upgraded
label: BODY

text: modules, presents satisfactory convergence results, and
label: BODY

text: summarizes the BLISS development status and the
label: BODY

text: future development direction.

text: Synopsis of BLISS
label: BODY

text: A synopsis of BLISS that also appeared in Agte et al,
label: BODY

text: 1999 is as follows.
label: BODY

text: BLISS is a method for optimization of engineering
label: BODY

text: systems that separates the system-level optimization
label: BODY

text: from potentially numerous autonomous subsystem
label: BODY

text: optimizations.  As shown in Figure 1, it utilizes a
label: BODY

text: system architecture in which design and behavior
label: BODY

text: variables are split into three categories.  X-variables are
label: BODY

text: those design variables optimized at the local level and
label: BODY

text: are unique to each particular subsystem.  Behavior
label: BODY

text: variables that are output from one subsystem and input
label: BODY

text: to another are designated Y, and the system-level
label: BODY

text: design variables are specified as Z.  System-level
label: BODY

text: variables are those shared by at least two subsystems.

text: After a best guess initialization, the first step in the
label: BODY

text: BLISS begins with the system analysis and sensitivity
label: BODY

text: analysis in which Y and the derivatives of Y with
label: BODY

text: respect to Z and X are computed.  A linear
label: BODY

text: approximation to the system objective (an element of
label: BODY

text: Y) as a function of Z and X is established using the
label: BODY

text: above derivatives.  That approximation is adopted as
label: BODY

text: the objective function in subdomain optimizations that
label: BODY

text: follow next.  In each subdomain (module, or black
label: BODY

text: box), the Z and Y variables are frozen and an
label: BODY

text: improvement in the objective function is sought by the
label: BODY

text: local optimizations that use local X separately in each
label: BODY

text: module.  The frozen Z and Y are constant parameters in
label: BODY

text: each module optimization and the module optimization
label: BODY

text: is followed by computation of the derivatives of the
label: BODY

text: optimum with respect to these parameters.  The second
label: BODY

text: step achieves improvement through the system-level
label: BODY

text: variables Z and is linked to the first step by the
label: BODY

text: derivatives of optimum with respect to parameters Z
label: BODY

text: and Y.  The derivatives are used to extrapolate each
label: BODY

text: subdomain optimum as a function of Z and Y.  The
label: BODY

text: functional relation Y=Y(Z) is
label: BODY

text: approximated
label: BODY

text: extrapolation based on the system sensitivity analysis.
label: BODY

text: These steps alternate until convergence.  A flowchart of
label: BODY

text: the method is shown in Figure 2.

text: Upgrades in the BLISS Structures and
label: BODY

text: Aerodynamics Modules
label: BODY

text: The modularity of BLISS permits replacing or adding
label: BODY

text: black boxes to refine or alter the optimization and
label: BODY

text: analysis tools in each modules allowing the engineer
label: BODY

text: the flexibility to exercise his judgment.  Having tools
label: BODY

text: of different level of fidelity in the modules enables
label: BODY

text: applications of BLISS in different design phases.  The
label: BODY

text: advanced BLISS method incorporates two new modules
label: BODY

text: that can be used in lieu of previous black boxes.  The
label: BODY

text: structures module now can use the Equivalent
label: BODY

text: Laminated Plate Solution (ELAPS, Giles, 1986) and
label: BODY

text: the aerodynamics module can use a code called
label: BODY

text: AWAVE (Harris, 1964) to perform wave drag analysis.
label: BODY

text: Integration of ELAPS
label: BODY

text: In the previous application example, BLISS employed
label: BODY

text: a skin-stringer representation of the internal wing box
label: BODY

text: bays.  This model broke the wing down into a three
label: BODY

text: bay wing box whose geometry varied with the taper
label: BODY

text: ratio, wing sweep, thickness to chord ratio, wingspan,
label: BODY

text: and aspect ratio, all manipulated as design variables in
label: BODY

text: the system-level optimization.  The displacements,
label: BODY

text: e.g., the wing twist, and stresses, were computed using
label: BODY

text: simple, thin-walled box-beam formulas (e.g., Bruhn,
label: BODY

text: In the BLISS application shown herein, the level of
label: BODY

text: accuracy in this module is raised by substituting the
label: BODY

text: previous model with the Equivalent Laminated Plate
label: BODY

text: American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics
label: BODY

text: Solution (ELAPS) computer code.  This code designed
label: BODY

text: with preliminary design stage calculations in mind is
label: BODY

text: capable of modeling aircraft wing structures with
label: BODY

text: multiple trapezoidal segments.  The wing structure is
label: BODY

text: represented as a plate whose stiffness is set equivalent
label: BODY

text: to that of the original, built-up, structural box of the
label: BODY

text: wing.  ELAPS employs a set of displacement functions
label: BODY

text: defined over each trapezoidal segment and made
label: BODY

text: compatible in regard to translations and rotations at the
label: BODY

text: segment junctions.  Minimization of the strain energy
label: BODY

text: based on the Ritz method leads to equations from
label: BODY

text: which to calculate static deflections and internal forces.
label: BODY

text: The latter are then converted to stresses taking into
label: BODY

text: account the details of the wing box built-up cross-
label: BODY

text: section.
label: BODY

text: The accuracy of the results of ELAPS has been found to
label: BODY

text: be somewhat below that of finite element codes (Giles,
label: BODY

text: 1986) but the ELAPS input is much simpler and faster
label: BODY

text: to develop.  The computation time for an ELAPS
label: BODY

text: model is more than an order of magnitude faster than
label: BODY

text: that of an equivalent finite element model - an
label: BODY

text: important feature for a tool to be integrated into an
label: BODY

text: optimization procedure.
label: BODY

text: Integrated in BLISS, ELAPS receives its input from a
label: BODY

text: pre-processor routine that generates an input file with
label: BODY

text: the skin thickness, aspect ratio, taper ratio, thickness to
label: BODY

text: chord ratio, sweep, reference area, and aircraft weight.
label: BODY

text: The model used by ELAPS analyzes stress along the
label: BODY

text: same three bay wingbox configuration used as an
label: BODY

text: example in the original application of BLISS.  Each
label: BODY

text: wingbox consists of the top and bottom sandwich
label: BODY

text: panels of different thicknesses and sandwich webs
label: BODY

text: identical in the front and rear of the wingbox.  The
label: BODY

text: front spar of the wing box is located at 10% of the
label: BODY

text: chord length and the rear spar lies at 70% of the chord
label: BODY

text: length.  Figure 3 depicts the configuration of the
label: BODY

text: ELAPS model used by BLISS.

label: BODY

text: As it was done in the original BLISS implementation,
label: BODY

text: the aerodynamic loads are being generated within the
label: BODY

text: structures module in the pre-processor to structural
label: BODY

text: analysis.  To calculate the lift loads on the wing, the
label: BODY

text: pre-processor routine averages spanwise between an
label: BODY

text: elliptical lift distribution and a linear distribution that
label: BODY

text: reflects the wing chord taper.  The elliptical and taper
label: BODY

text: ratio based lift distributions for the wing are each
label: BODY

text: normalized to contain an area of unity as illustrated in
label: BODY

text: Figure 5.  The averaged, spanwise load distribution is
label: BODY

text: multiplied by the lift required from the wing and
label: BODY

text: distributed chordwise. The chordwise distribution is a
label: BODY

text: typical supersonic one with the center of pressure
label: BODY

text: located at 50% of the chord.  The aerodynamic load
label: BODY

text: distribution would be expected to be calculated by an
label: BODY

text: aerodynamics module using a higher fidelity analysis,
label: BODY

text: e.g., a computational fluid dynamics code.  Thus, the
label: BODY

text: present aerodynamic loads generation is merely a
label: BODY

text: placeholder for a real aerodynamic loads analysis in a
label: BODY

text: future BLISS upgrade.
label: BODY

text: In summary, the structural module employs ELAPS to
label: BODY

text: calculate the stresses in the wing box for the given
label: BODY

text: configuration, lift distribution, and corresponding
label: BODY

text: constraints.  It also outputs the wing twist and weight
label: BODY

text: and the objective function for the local optimization.
label: BODY

text: The aerodynamics module accepts the output and
label: BODY

text: models its influence on the aerodynamic response.

text: Integration of AWAVE
label: HH1

text: The cruise segment of the test case mission is
label: BODY

text: supersonic.  The original model (Sobieszczanski-
label: BODY

text: Sobieski et al, 1998) used an approximation relying on
label: BODY

text: the span efficiency factor.  That approximation was
label: BODY

text: replaced herein with a code, AWAVE, that is a
label: BODY

text: streamlined version of the far-field wave drag program
label: BODY

text: (Harris, 1964).  There are two versions of the Harris
label: BODY

text: wave drag program in common use at LaRC.  The
label: BODY

text: original version, described in the reference, treats lifting
label: BODY

text: surfaces as a series of 3-dimensional solid elements.  A
label: BODY

text: much faster but slightly less accurate version treats
label: BODY

text: lifting surfaces as 2-dimensional panels with finite
label: BODY

text: thicknesses.  Due to compensating errors at positive
label: BODY

text: and negative roll angles of the Mach cutting plane, the
label: BODY

text: panel version gives excellent results for wave drag
label: BODY

text: coefficients.  The objective of the last (AWAVE) effort
label: BODY

text: was to develop a version of the wave drag program with
label: BODY

text: the accuracy of the solid element program that is faster
label: BODY

text: than the panel version.
label: BODY

text: The AWAVE code
label: BODY

text: implemented computes the wave drag on the basis of
label: BODY

text: the
label: BODY

text: aircraft cross-section distribution
label: BODY

text: along
label: BODY

text: the
label: BODY

text: centerline, hence it requires data about the entire
label: BODY

text: configuration geometry to enable the area ruling of
label: BODY

text: supersonic body design.
label: BODY

text: Similarly to the integration of ELAPS, integration of
label: BODY

text: AWAVE was accomplished by creating a pre-processor
label: BODY

text: to generate the necessary input.  The input provides the
label: BODY

text: current designÕs aspect ratio, taper ratio, thickness to
label: BODY

text: chord ratio, sweep angle, wing reference area, horizontal
label: BODY

text: tail sweep angle, horizontal tail aspect ratio, and
label: BODY

text: horizontal tail reference area.  The pre-processor also
label: BODY

text: creates and places the wing and tail airfoils according to
label: BODY

text: the design configuration variables.  The AWAVE
label: BODY

text: output is the wave drag coefficient to be added to the
label: BODY

text: other drag components whose calculation remains the
label: BODY

text: same as in the original BLISS.

text: In the original BLISS, the taper ratio was a local
label: BODY

text: variable of the structures module.  With the integration
label: BODY

text: of ELAPS and AWAVE, the taper ratio affects both the
label: BODY

text: aerodynamics and structures module.  While the
label: BODY

text: aerodynamics module optimization may tend toward a
label: BODY

text: taper ratio to reduce induced drag, the structures module
label: BODY

text: may generate a different taper value to reduce stresses.
label: BODY

text: To resolve this trade-off, the taper ratio was raised to a
label: BODY

text: system variable, capable of influencing both modules.
label: BODY

text: Figure 6 shows the current black box and variable
label: BODY

text: interactions.
label: BODY

text: In this model there are nine system-level Z-variables,
label: BODY

text: each influencing a minimum of two of the subsystems.
label: BODY

text: The local variables of each subsystem are manipulated
label: BODY

text: only in the optimization local to that subsystem.  The
label: BODY

text: propulsion module has the throttle as its sole local
label: BODY

text: variable.  In the present state of BLISS, the range
label: BODY

text: module is an exception as it performs no optimization.
label: BODY

text: It only evaluates the Breguet range formula.  The
label: BODY

text: aerodynamics module optimizes the local variables of
label: BODY

text: American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics
label: BODY

text: the horizontal tail sweep as well as the variables that
label: BODY

text: place the wing and tail along the fuselage axis.  The
label: BODY

text: structural subsystem optimization operates on the
label: BODY

text: sandwich face sheet and caliper thicknesses for the wing
label: BODY

text: cover panels and the webs of the three wingbox bays.
label: BODY

text: The ten Y-variables noted in the off-diagonal boxes in
label: BODY

text: Figure 6, represent couplings of the black boxes and are
label: BODY

text: computed in the system analysis.
label: BODY

text: BLISS was originally implemented in MATLAB 5.3.0
label: BODY

text: at both the system and subsystem levels.  The
label: BODY

text: MATLAB Optimization Toolbox was used as an
label: BODY

text: optimizer in the subsystem and system optimizations.
label: BODY

text: In the version of BLISS reported herein, the use of
label: BODY

text: MATLAB continued as above with the exception of the
label: BODY

text: structures and aerodynamics modules that incorporated
label: BODY

text: ELAPS and AWAVE, both written in FORTRAN 77.
label: BODY

text: MATLAB provides a facility to invoke FORTRAN
label: BODY

text: from a MATLAB code. To exploit that facility, the
label: BODY

text: preprocessors to both ELAPS and AWAVE were
label: BODY

text: written in FORTRAN and converted into MEX-Files
label: BODY

text: using the MATLAB mex-function (Appendix).  Both
label: BODY

text: AWAVE and ELAPS were then directly called from
label: BODY

text: within the BLISS modules.  On the output side,
label: BODY

text: simple post-processing generated outputs in a format
label: BODY

text: acceptable to the parts of BLISS that remained being
label: BODY

text: coded in MATLAB for further analysis. Because of the
label: BODY

text: MATLAB ability to invoke FORTRAN codes, the
label: BODY

text: BLISS upgrading process may continue by adding
label: BODY

text: FORTRAN-coded modules wherever required while
label: BODY

text: retaining the MATLAB core that executes the method
label: BODY

text: logic illustrated by the flowchart in Fig. 1.
label: BODY

text: The next step in the BLISS development is to
label: BODY

text: incorporate additional modules to increase the analysis
label: BODY

text: fidelity.  The largest refinement would be expected
label: BODY

text: from adding a computational fluid dynamics code to
label: BODY

text: perform the aerodynamic analysis, including the loads.
label: BODY

text: The propulsion data quality would benefit from
label: BODY

text: replacing the current response surface fitted to a look-up
label: BODY

text: table with a comprehensive engine analysis.  Also, the
label: BODY

text: simple Breguet formula for the aircraft range would
label: BODY

text: need to be replaced by a complete performance analysis
label: BODY

text: Conclusions and Remarks
label: H4

text: Integration of ELAPS and AWAVE into BLISS
label: BODY

text: demonstrated the modular nature of the method and its
label: BODY

text: ability to accommodate refinements.  Used in a limited
label: BODY

text: test case of a supersonic business jet design, the two-
label: BODY

text: level optimization in BLISS was effective in satisfying
label: BODY

text: the system-level and local constraints while attaining a
label: BODY

text: system-level objective within a reasonable number of
label: BODY

text: iterations.  Separation of the system-level design
label: BODY

text: variables from the local ones enabled optimization for a
label: BODY

text: system-level objective while providing autonomy of the
label: BODY

text: design decision and tool choice within disciplines
label: BODY

text: represented in the modules.

text: The method is open to further upgrades in terms of the
label: BODY

text: fidelity of analysis and optimization techniques
label: BODY

text: employed in the modules.  In this regard, it is up to the
label: BODY

text: user to decide on the variety of tools to be integrated in
label: BODY

text: BLISS as needed by the multidisciplinary optimization
label: BODY

text: task at hand.
label: BODY

text: Further advancement of BLISS from its present status
label: BODY

text: of a method concept demonstrator to a tool useful in
label: BODY

text: actual applications calls for inserting a CFD code in the
label: BODY

text: aerodynamics module, adding a comprehensive engine
label: BODY

text: analysis to the propulsion module, and extending the
label: BODY

text: performance analysis module to include more than just
label: BODY

text: the cruise phase of a mission.
label: BODY

text: Finally, as the increased fidelity of analyses in the
label: BODY

text: modules will exact its price in terms of the computing
label: BODY

text: elapsed time, concurrent execution of the modular
label: BODY

text: analyses and optimizations will become an attractive
label: BODY

text: option.

text: There are a few steps required for integrating a
label: BODY

text: FORTRAN code into the MATLAB environment that
label: BODY

text: BLISS is currently programmed in.  The user must
label: BODY

text: locate the place in BLISS where a call is made to
label: BODY

text: analysis that is to be replaced.  Then he must examine
label: BODY

text: the input and output of the new and old analysis to
label: BODY

text: ensure that the remainder of BLISS is capable of
label: BODY

text: supplying input the new analysis requires and that the
label: BODY

text: new analysis produces all the output expected.  Then a
label: BODY

text: American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics
label: BODY

text: pre-processor routine must be created to present the
label: BODY

text: variable information to the FORTRAN code in an
label: BODY

text: appropriate format.  Finally the data must be harvested
label: BODY

text: and returned to the MATLAB module from which the
label: BODY

text: FORTRAN code is being called in a format compatible
label: BODY

text: with MATLAB.
label: BODY

text: Pre-processing
label: HH1

text: In pre-processing, BLISS must pass the needed
label: BODY

text: variables to a routine which will manipulate them into
label: BODY

text: a form that the FORTRAN code will accept.  The
label: BODY

text: programmer must first ensure that the module in which
label: BODY

text: he is pre-processing has access to the required variables
label: BODY

text: (i.e., the subsystem must not be using X variables
label: BODY

text: assigned to other subsystems).
label: BODY

text: The two
label: BODY

text: FORTRAN
label: BODY

text: codes integrated
label: BODY

text: required
label: BODY

text: formatted text input files.  The easiest way to prepare
label: BODY

text: these files was to use a FORTRAN subroutine to take
label: BODY

text: the design variables, configure them in the way needed
label: BODY

text: to represent the geometry or conditions needed by the
label: BODY

text: analysis, and write the formatted input file for analysis.
label: BODY

text: In order to pass variables from the MATLAB
label: BODY

text: environment
label: BODY

text: the
label: BODY

text: FORTRAN
label: BODY

text: pre-processing
label: BODY

text: subroutine, MATLABÕs mex-function was invoked.  In

label: BODY

text: the FORTRAN pre-processing subroutine.  This new
label: BODY

text: routine collects an array of variables passed in from

text: routine using the mex command.  This creates a mex-
label: BODY

text: file which is treated as a MATLAB function requiring
label: BODY

text: an input array and an output array.  The user then places
label: BODY

text: his variables for the pre-processing function into an
label: BODY

text: array and puts this array into the new mex-file.  This
label: BODY

text: sends the variables to the gateway routine which
label: BODY

text: assigns them to the variables used in the FORTRAN
label: BODY

text: pre-processing subroutine.  The input file is generated
label: BODY

text: and control returns to MATLAB.
label: BODY

text: Program Insertion
label: HH1

text: Having prepared the data for analysis by the program,
label: BODY

text: the programmer must locate the section of BLISS that
label: BODY

text: he wishes to upgrade.  The previous analysis must be
label: BODY

text: removed and the code must be placed such that BLISS
label: BODY

text: will have performed the new analysis and have data
label: BODY

text: ready for later analysis that the user is not replacing.
label: BODY

text: Having located the desired calling spot and removed the
label: BODY

text: replaced analysis, the user simply calls the program
label: BODY

text: from within BLISS.  By previously compiling the
label: BODY

text: FORTRAN code in question, the user calls the program
label: BODY

text: by typing !program_name in the BLISS code where
label: BODY

text: program_name is the command that runs the program
label: BODY

text: from the operating system.  The program then processes
label: BODY

text: the prepared input file and returns to BLISS.
label: BODY

text: Data Collection
label: BODY

text: The final step that the programmer must perform in
label: BODY

text: order for BLISS to carry on its optimization is
label: BODY

text: harvesting the data produced by the new program.
label: BODY

text: ELAPS and AWAVE both created output files with
label: BODY

text: data required for BLISS.  There are two basic ways to
label: BODY

text: collect data produced by FORTRAN codes.
label: BODY

text: The first way is to use a post-processing technique
label: BODY

text: similar to that of pre-processing. The user would create
label: BODY

text: a search algorithm to locate and collect the data from
label: BODY

text: the output file.  This in turn would be harvested by
label: BODY

text: using the mex-function to create a gateway between the
label: BODY

text: FORTRAN data collection routine and the BLISS
label: BODY

text: variables.  The programmer would compile the mex-
label: BODY

text: function gateway routine combined with his data
label: BODY

text: collection routine, run the new mex-file with an array
label: BODY

text: prepared to collect the output of the routine, and extract
label: BODY

text: his data to the array.  The programmer would then need
label: BODY

text: to assign the array variables to the proper variables in
label: BODY

text: the BLISS code.  This technique would be best for
label: BODY

text: cases where the user did not have access to the source
label: BODY

text: code of the FORTRAN program.
label: BODY

text: In cases where the programmer does have the
label: BODY

text: FORTRAN programÕs source code and a fair knowledge
label: BODY

text: of how the program works, he can edit the code to
label: BODY

text: output the needed results in a format compatible with
label: BODY

text: MATLAB.  If the user can locate the sections of code
label: BODY

text: that write out the results to the output file, they can
label: BODY

text: change the code to output to a file with a .m extension.
label: BODY

text: Files in this format are recognized as MATLAB
label: BODY

text: programs that can be called without FORTRAN
label: BODY

text: interaction.  By creating .m files with MATLAB
label: BODY

text: variable assignments corresponding to the data that the
label: BODY

text: user wishes to collect, the programmer simply runs
label: BODY

text: these MATLAB files after completion of the main
label: BODY

text: program call and the output is already in MATLAB
label: BODY

text: format.  This avoids unnecessary data file searching and
label: BODY

text: reduces MATLAB-FORTRAN interaction.  After the
label: BODY

text: data are collected and assigned to the proper variables in
label: BODY

text: BLISS, the analysis would then continue as normal.
label: BODY
